    "review::.::holistic::logic_clarity::parseCommitCount_redundant_param": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::logic_clarity::parseCommitCount_redundant_param",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 2,
      "confidence": "medium",
      "summary": "parseCommitCount 'responseOk' parameter is always equivalent to 'linkHeader !== null || response exists'",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "logic_clarity",
        "related_files": [
          "src/lib/utils/github.ts"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "fetchGitHub returns null for non-ok responses, so when commitsRes is non-null, the response was ok. The caller passes 'commitsRes !== null' as responseOk, which is tautologically true when commitsRes exists (line 71). The fallback 'return responseOk ? 1 : 0' is reached only when linkHeader has no match, and at that point responseOk is always true because commitsRes was non-null to reach this code path."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Remove the responseOk parameter from parseCommitCount. The function only needs the linkHeader string. If no Link header match is found, return 1 (a valid response with no pagination means exactly 1 page of commits). The caller simplifies to parseCommitCount(commitsRes?.headers.get('Link') ?? null).",
        "reasoning": "",
        "content_hash": "3148b8ec"
      },
      "status": "wontfix",
      "note": "Not redundant: responseOk distinguishes no-response (0) from response-without-Link (1 commit)",
      "first_seen": "2026-03-12T08:59:56+00:00",
