    "review::.::holistic::error_consistency::silent_error_swallowing": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::error_consistency::silent_error_swallowing",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 1,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "fetchGitHub catches all errors and returns null without logging or preserving error context",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "error_consistency",
        "related_files": [
          "src/lib/utils/github.ts"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "The catch block on line 11 catches any error and returns null. A rate limit (429), network failure, DNS error, and server error (500) all produce the same null result. No console.warn, no error categorization, no way for callers to distinguish failure modes. During build-time SSG, a rate-limited API call silently produces empty GitHub data with no build log evidence."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Add a console.warn in the catch block logging the URL and error message. Consider returning a discriminated result type like { ok: false, reason: 'network' | 'rate_limit' | 'not_found' | 'server_error' } instead of bare null, or at minimum log the HTTP status code for non-ok responses before returning null.",
        "reasoning": "",
        "content_hash": "34556ba1"
      },
      "status": "open",
      "note": null,
      "first_seen": "2026-03-12T08:59:56+00:00",
      "last_seen": "2026-03-12T09:00:10+00:00",
      "resolved_at": null,
      "reopen_count": 0,
      "lang": "typescript",
      "suppressed": false,
      "suppressed_at": null,
      "suppression_pattern": null
    },
    "review::.::holistic::error_consistency::broad_catch_no_discrimination": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::error_consistency::broad_catch_no_discrimination",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 1,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "fetchGitHub conflates non-ok HTTP responses with network/parse exceptions into a single null",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "error_consistency",
        "related_files": [
          "src/lib/utils/github.ts"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "Lines 8-9 check res.ok and return null for non-ok responses. Lines 10-13 catch network exceptions and also return null. These are fundamentally different failure modes (the server responded with an error vs the request never completed) but produce identical results. A 403 rate limit could be retried after a delay; a network error might indicate a build environment issue."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Separate the non-ok response path from the exception path. For non-ok responses, log the status code (res.status) and consider special handling for 403/429 (rate limit). For caught exceptions, log the error. Even if both ultimately return null for graceful degradation, the logging distinction aids debugging.",
        "reasoning": "",
        "content_hash": "91942d7a"
      },
      "status": "open",
      "note": null,
      "first_seen": "2026-03-12T08:59:56+00:00",
      "last_seen": "2026-03-12T09:00:10+00:00",
      "resolved_at": null,
